The better world is already here
KOPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have been discussing the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which an ever-growing number of people mean less food, where increasing resource demand leads to plundering and war, and where the rising production capacity of the past decades brings more pollution and global warming in its wake.
One of the sacred texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits of Growth, still influences the environmental movement today.
On the other hand, the optimists claim that everything will get better – human health, living standards, environmental quality, and so on.
From their opponents, they are seen as "economists of abundance" who trust the market, which allegedly solves all problems.
But instead of picking facts and stories that fit into a big narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see if the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this is what I tried to achieve together with 21 leading economists worldwide by developing a rating list of the past 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender ratio, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists have answered the same question: How high were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including forecasts up to 2050.
Using classical economic evaluations of all factors from death tolls, health damage, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands and higher hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To estimate the extent of the problem, it is compared to the solution with the total resources available.
By doing this, the size of the problem becomes clear as a share of the GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let's consider the inequality of the sexes.
Basically, we excluded almost half of the world's population from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the workforce worldwide was of female gender.
What losses occurred from this low percentage?
Even if we take into account the higher costs of women's education and the unpaid household work that someone has to do, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the global GDP of 1900.
Today, with a higher female participation rate and smaller income differences, the loss is 7% – and will probably fall to 4% by 2050.
It will probably come as a surprise that the climate change from 1900 to 2025 will likely bring mostly a growing net benefit – which will rise to 1.5% of GDP per year.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. When it occurs at a moderate level, the benefits prevail.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 entries were a blessing for agriculture since the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect at a height of 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, a moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces the heating demand more strongly than it creates new cooling demand, which corresponds to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems like wetlands, which corresponds to a loss of about 0.1%.
With further rising temperatures, however, costs rise and benefits fall, which dramatically reduces the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs worldwide, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the valuation list also shows us that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from air pollution in indoor spaces due to harmful emissions from cooking and heating. This corresponds to a loss of 3% of the world's GDP.
But in 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved the most all over the world.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy hardly changed.
The size of the profit since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and probably 76 years by 2050).
The biggest influencing factor was the decline in infant mortality.
For example, as late as 1970, only 5% of newborns were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which has led to the rescue of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved through world peace throughout the 20th century.
This success has been achieved by many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent over $2.5 billion on vaccines and promised another $10 billion.
Through efforts of the Rotary club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the 20th century were an astonishing 32% of the world's GDP.
Today they have decreased to about 11% and will halve again by 2050.
Even if optimists are not right in all aspects (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of the GDP annually, and much more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the issues examined show improvements of 5-20% of the GDP.
And the general trend is even clearer.
Relative to the resources available to combat them, the global problems have dramatically decreased.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no more problems.
Although they have decreased in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and small trade, they are still quite large.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has greatly improved.
Furthermore, the rating list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not orient our view of the future to the most terrifying stories or the loudest interest groups, but to objective assessments of which areas we can achieve the greatest improvements.
